A carcinoma of the lung may have been present for several years before reaching a size at which it can be seen by chest roentgenogram 
Many of the previous widespread screening uses of the chest roentgenogram have been abandoned 
Mass chest x ray screening for tuberculosis has not been cost effective for the past  years 
Screening for lung cancer is controversial 
Screening x rays in routine hospital admissions have been challenged 
Screening chest x rays in patients under age  prior to elective surgery also seems to be of little value 
The chest x ray is  however  valuable in following the resolution of pneumonia and the increase in size of undiagnosed pulmonary lesions  as well as in assessing suspected pulmonary disease 
